 contours of imperial rule.The volume reaches from Peru to New Zealand to Europe to capture the varieties and continuities of legal pluralism and to probe the analytic power of the concept of legal pluralism in the comparative study of empires. For legal scholars, social scientists, and historians, Legal Pluralism and Empires, 1500-1850 maps new approaches to the study of empires and the global history of law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aColoniesxCongressesxLaw and legislation. 0aColoniesxLaw and legislationvCongresses. 0aLegal polycentricityvCongresses. 0aLegal polycentricityxCongresses. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBarkey, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenton, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenton, Lauren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurbank, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewar, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalliday, Paul D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcHugh, P. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwensby, Brian P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Richard J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRupert, Linda M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStern, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe